    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "To maximize speed, we can simplify the moving average calculation by using a fixed-size buffer and only tracking the sum directly, ignoring the timestamp in the average calculation. Here is the optimized version using a deque for efficient window management:\n\n```python\nfrom collections import deque\n\ndef process_sensor_data_optimized(data_stream):\n    window = deque(maxlen=11)\n    total = 0.0\n    smoothed_values = []\n\n    for timestamp, value in data_stream:\n        if len(window) == 11:\n            total -= window[0]  # Remove oldest value from sum\n        \n        window.append(value)  # Add new value to sum and buffer\n        total += value\n        \n        # Calculate average and use the current timestamp\n        avg = total / len(window)\n        smoothed_values.append((timestamp, avg))\n    return smoothed_values\n```\n\nBy using `deque`'s `maxlen`, we achieve $O(1)$ time complexity for adding and removing elements, which is the fastest possible for this sliding window scenario.",
